# Your rule content
User will pass the component path, example: /pages/operaciones/pedidos/nota-recepcion/historico-nota-recepcion/
User will pass the component name, example: historico-nota-recepcion
User will pass what parameters should this component receive on routing, example: id
You will create a component ts, html, scss
You will register the component in corresponding module and add the a rounting to this component on the corresponding routing module
If user indicates that this component will be a dialog (modal) do not create routing
The html structure will be this:
<ion-content>
  <ion-row style="align-items: center">
    <ion-col size="2">
      <ion-icon name="arrow-back" style="font-size: 1.5em" (click)="onBack()"></ion-icon>
    </ion-col>
    <ion-col size="8" style="text-align: center">component name</ion-col>
  </ion-row>
  <ion-grid fixed>
  </ion-grid>
</ion-content>
<ion-footer>
  if user indicates that this component will be a model, create those buttons:
  <ion-row>
      <ion-col>
        <ion-button expand="block" class="btn-danger" (click)="onCancel()">
          Cancelar
        </ion-button>
      </ion-col>
      <ion-col>
        <ion-button expand="block" class="btn-success" (click)="onConfirm()">
          Confirmar
        </ion-button>
      </ion-col>
    </ion-row>
</ion-footer>

if user do not indicate that component will be a modal do this:
on .ts file you will import on constructor:
import { Location } from '@angular/common';
and create this method:
onBack() {
    this._location.back();
}

else do this:
create a interface with data the user pass for us and name it ComponentNameData
create an input to receive the data, example:
@Input()
  data: NotaRecepcionInfoDialogData;
create onCancel and onConfirm methods, onCancel should close modal and return null




